<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06129h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06129h">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06129h"> 129(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 100s of chapelles</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est surtout par le culte des saints qu&apos;elle &eacute;tait caract&eacute;ris&eacute;e. Entre tant de particularit&eacute;s que la Bretagne poss&egrave;de en propre, l&apos;hagiographie locale est s&ucirc;rement la plus singuli&egrave;re. Quand on visite &agrave; pied le pays, une chose frappe au premier coup d&apos;&oelig;il. Les &eacute;glises paroissiales, o&ugrave; se fait le culte du dimanche, ne diff&egrave;rent pas essentiellement de celles des autres pays. Que si l&apos;on parcourt la <font color="green">[79]</font> cam-pagne, au contraire, on rencontre souvent dans une seule paroisse jusqu&apos;&agrave; <mark>dix et quinze chapelles</mark>, petites maisonnettes n&apos;ayant le plus souvent qu&apos;une porte et une fen&ecirc;tre, et d&eacute;di&eacute;es &agrave; un saint dont on n&apos;a jamais en-tendu parler dans le reste de la chr&eacute;tient&eacute;. <mark>Ces saints locaux, que l&apos;on compte par centaines</mark>, sont tous du ve ou du vie si&egrave;cle, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire de l&apos;&eacute;poque de l&apos;&eacute;migration; ce sont des personnages ayant pour la plupart r&eacute;ellement exist&eacute;, mais que la l&eacute;gende a entour&eacute;s du plus brillant r&eacute;seau de fables. <font color="green">[It was especially by the cult of the saints that it was characterized. Between so many particularities that Brittany has its own, local hagiography is surely the most singular. When visiting the country on foot, something is striking at first glance. The parish churches, where Sunday worship is held, do not differ essentially from those of other countries. That if one travels through the countryside, on the contrary, one often meets in a single parish up to ten and fifteen chapels, little houses usually having only a door and a window, and dedicated to a saint whom we have never heard of in the rest of Christendom. These local saints, which number in the hundreds, are all of the fifth or sixth century, that is, of the period of emigration; they are characters who for the most part really existed, but whom the legend has surrounded by the most brilliant network of fables.]</font> <small> Ernest Renan, <a name="ERSD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ERSD"><cite title="source">Souvenirs d'enfance et de jeunesse</cite></a> (1883) 79-80</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
